{{com.atlassian.confluence.core.TimeZone}} does not provide a straightforward way of retrieving a timezone offset that considers daylight savings.

At the moment, this would be achieved as follows:
{code}TimeZone.getInstance("America/Los_Angeles").getWrappedTimeZone().getOffset(){code}

Additionally, {{TimeZone}} provides an instance method called {{getDisplayOffset()}}. Although we specify that [getDisplayOffset simply returns the raw offset in a printable format|https://developer.atlassian.com/static/javadoc/confluence/3.3.3/reference/com/atlassian/confluence/core/TimeZone.html#getInstance%28java.lang.String%29], it seems reasonable to think that an offset value suitable for display should take daylight savings into account.

*Steps to reproduce*
* On a page, type some text
* Use Ctrl+A or Cmd+A to select the entire text. Now hit Enter.

A JS error is thrown.
{code}
Index or size is negative or greater than the allowed amount
   ra.setStart(en, eo); 
{code}

This is a Firefox only bug.

Current support assumes the content is wiki and there is no option for storage format. This must have been missed when 4.0 was done. Need option for either wiki or storage format. Need to leave the wiki option as default so it doesn't cause a compatibility problem. 

Suggest adding an option in the extended service API that has the parameters parameter: String renderContent(String token, String spaceKey, String pageId, String content, Hashtable parameters).  Something like this:

{code:title=PagesSoapService}
public String renderContent(String spaceKey, long pageId, String newContent, Map parameters) throws RemoteException
    {
        ...
        if (StringUtils.isNotBlank(newContent))
        {
            String renderedContent;
            if ((parameters.containsKey("format") && "storage".equalsIgnoreCase((String parameters.get("format")) {
                renderedContent = renderContent(page.getSpaceKey(), page.getId(), newContent); 
            } else { 
                renderedContent = wikiStyleRenderer.convertWikiToXHtml(pageContext, newContent);
            }
        }
        ...
{code}

